I made these scones three times in as many weeks. The first two times, I used half a bag (about 6 ounces, 1-1/4 to 1-1/2 cups) of halved fresh cranberries and the peel of a very large orange (approximately 1-1/2 to 2 tablespoons). They were delicious but needed additional sweetness to counteract the tart flavor of fresh cranberries. I spread a thin layer of passion mango butter on top, and it was perfect. A glaze of orange juice and confectioner's sugar, or a sprinkling of sugar would work well, too. By the third time, I was out of fresh cranberries and used the specified dried cranberries. I continued to use more orange peel and replaced half of the all-purpose flour with whole wheat flour. This was my favorite version, even though I'm not a huge fan of whole wheat, which added lovely flavor here. Each time I made these, I made three smaller rounds and cut them into fourths, sixths, or eighths. That way, I had an assortment of sizes that were just right for breakfast or a snack. This scone has just the right amount of "shortness"--that dry, biscuity (not cakey) texture that I associate with scones. Perhaps the lack of eggs contributes to this presentation. They keep a nice crust if I freeze them right away. After 3 days in a plastic container on the counter, they tasted fresh enough to serve to guests, but the outside was soft and I finally froze the rest.

