July 2001: Sigh, what is my problem? I am an experienced baker and made this recipe very, very carefully three times. It is just too wet. Attempt 1: Too wet to be taken out of the bowl. Chilling it helped, but after baking it, the inside was wet and compressed. Attempt 2: Ran out of buttermilk, so I put it in the fridge, got buttermilk, and continued the next morning. Same results, of course. Attempt 3: Used 3/4 c buttermilk, though I probably should have stopped at 5/8c. Only slightly too wet this time. P.S. Using the zest from an entire orange is a good modification. April 2002: Now that I have a food processor, I decided to find out if the 4th time would be the charm. Yay, the dough was not wet at all! I must have been overworking the butter before or reading a measurement wrong? I feel a lot better now :) These were good and had the flaky, layered texture of biscuits. Again, I used the zest from one whole orange. Next time, I'm going to increase it even more or add some orange oil. Even though I made 12 scones instead of 8, I still wished I had decreased the oven temp slightly (and increased the baking time accordingly).

